{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505999"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:39:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:39:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2506"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2506"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.44,0.09,0.03,0.37]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2506"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108613"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2506"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2506"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90982"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1511"},{"type":"tags","id":"2310"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"12053"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2323"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2335"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7399"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7480"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11740"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17468"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18188"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40488"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108613"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old woman presents to the antenatal clinic at 37 weeks gestation with a one-week history of generalised pruritus. The itch began on her palms and soles and has now spread across her trunk and back. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her two previous pregnancies and deliveries were uncomplicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable with mild scleral icterus and multiple scratch marks across her arms. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 110/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender with a fundal height of 36 cm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 110 g/L (125-160)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 6 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet count 250 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProthrombin time 11 seconds (10-13)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal bilirubin 25 \u00b5mol/L (2-17)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDirect bilirubin 9 \u00b5mol/L (0-5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum bile acids 105 \u00b5mol/L (0.3-10)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST 150 U/L (12-38)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT 180 U/L (3-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHepatitis serology is negative. Abdominal and pelvic ultrasound scans are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassure and bed rest as there is no increased risk of stillbirth and maternal symptom management is the priority","Plan induction of labour immediately to reduce risk of stillbirth","Reassure and bed rest with weekly LFT\u0027s and bile acids to monitor for risk of stillbirth","Plan induction of labour at 39-40 weeks to reduce risk of stillbirth","Commence ursodeoxycholic acid to reduce risk of stillbirth"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with generalised pruritus and jaundice, with elevated bile acid and direct bilirubin levels. This is suggestive of intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy (ICP). ICP occurs most commonly during the third trimester. If left untreated, complications such as fetal growth restriction, preterm birth, or fetal death may occur. Definitive treatment involves \u003Cstrong\u003Einduction of labour\u003C/strong\u003E. Timing of induction of labour depends on the level of bile acid which gives some prediction to the risk for stillbirth. The pruritus spontaneously resolves after delivery. Induction of labour at this stage is crucial to prevent adverse fetal outcomes associated with ICP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk for Stillbirth as per the RCOG guidelines; \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn women with peak bile acids 19\u201339 micromol/L (mild ICP) and no other risk factors, advise them that the risk of stillbirth is similar to the background risk. Consider options of planned birth by 40 weeks\u0027 gestation or ongoing antenatal care according to national guidance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn women with peak bile acids 40\u201399 micromol/L (moderate ICP) and no other risk factors, advise them that the known risk of stillbirth is similar to the background risk until 38\u201339 weeks\u0027 gestation. Consider planned birth at 38\u201339 weeks\u0027 gestation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn women with peak bile acids 100 micromol/L or more (severe ICP), advise them that the risk of stillbirth is higher than the background risk. Consider planned birth at 35\u201336 weeks\u0027 gestation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassure and bed rest\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as intrahepatic cholestasis is usually not self-limiting, and the risk of complications will progress if left untreated. The condition carries a significant risk of stillbirth that increases with advancing gestation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeekly monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E of liver function tests and bile acids would be appropriate earlier in pregnancy or at lower bile acid levels, but in this case with high bile acids the priority is to deliver the baby to prevent potential complications rather than continue monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelaying induction\u003C/strong\u003E until 39-40 weeks would expose the fetus to unnecessary risk in this case due to bile acids \u003E100. This may be appropriate with lower bile acid levels. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrsodeoxycholic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is not effective in reducing adverse perinatal outcomes and does not decrease maternal itch nor maternal bile acid concentrations, as demonstrated in the PITCHES trial. While it may be used earlier in pregnancy to manage symptoms, it is not the definitive treatment at term.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of ICP is supported by the characteristic symptoms of pruritus (particularly affecting palms and soles), elevated bile acids (\u003E10 \u00b5mol/L), and elevated liver transaminases. The condition typically resolves after delivery but may recur in subsequent pregnancies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Induction of labour at term is the most appropriate management of intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy at term. Timing of induction of labour depends on the severity of bile acids.","Ursodeoxycholic acid is not effective in reducing adverse perinatal outcomes in intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy but may be used to manage maternal itch symptoms."],"references":["Girling J, Knight CL, Chappell L, Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy: Green-top Guideline No. 43. BJOG [Internet]. 2022 Aug 9 [cited 2024 Dec 4]; Available from: https://doi.org/10.1111/1471-0528.17206.","Chappell L, Bell J, Smith A, Linsell L, Juszczak E, Dixon P et al. Ursodeoxycholic acid versus placebo in women with intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy (PITCHES): a randomised controlled trial. The Lancet. 2019;394(10201):849-860. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31378395/","Pataia V, Dixon PH, Williamson C. Pregnancy and bile acid disorders. Am J Physiol Gastrointest Liver Physiol. 2017; 313:G1. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28450276/","Nielsen JH, Lykke JA. Differentiated timing of induction for women with intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy-A historical cohort study. Acta Obstet Gynecol Scand. 2021 Feb;100(2):279-285. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32970824/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90982"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2506"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90982"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-12T12:59:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-12T20:07:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2506"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108613"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"at